a neurotransmitter?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excitatory motor neurones","Inhibitory motor neurones","Ascending interneurones","Descending interneurones","Sensory neurones"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe myenteric plexus contains several types of neurones that coordinate gastrointestinal motility:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcitatory motor neurones\u003C/strong\u003E use Substance P and acetylcholine as their primary neurotransmitters to stimulate smooth muscle contraction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibitory motor neurones\u003C/strong\u003E primarily use nitric oxide and vasoactive intestinal peptide to cause muscle relaxation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAscending interneurones\u003C/strong\u003E primarily use acetylcholine to coordinate proximal contraction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDescending interneurones\u003C/strong\u003E use serotonin and other neurotransmitters to coordinate distal relaxation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory neurones\u003C/strong\u003E use various neurotransmitters to detect mechanical and chemical stimuli\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESubstance P is particularly important in excitatory motor neurones where it works alongside acetylcholine to promote smooth muscle contraction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Substance P is a key excitatory neurotransmitter in the enteric nervous system, particularly in motor neurones that stimulate smooth muscle contraction","Excitatory motor neurones in the myenteric plexus use both Substance P and acetylcholine as their primary neurotransmitters","Different types of enteric neurones use distinct neurotransmitter combinations to coordinate gastrointestinal motility"],"references":["Chen BN, Humenick A, Yew WP, Peterson RA, Wiklendt L, Dinning PG, Spencer NJ, Wattchow DA, Costa M, Brookes SJH. 